    <h1>Development workflow</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <p>In Scrum different workflows to develop, test and deploy the sof=
tware can be implemented. The specific workflow can depend on the size and =
complexity of the project and many other considerations. Here follows an ex=
ample of workflow. The following tools are assumed to be used to develop, b=
uild, test and deploy the software in two environments, test and production=
: Bitbucket (or Github), JIRA, Bamboo.</p>
<ol>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: decimal;"><p><span>The customer and the produ=
ct owner create issues and store them in the product backlog. An issue cont=
ains a description of the work that must be done, the acceptance criteria o=
f its solution</span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: decimal;"><p><span>The product owner and the =
team make an estimation of the effort (e.g. in story points, using perhaps =
</span><a href=3D"https://www.mountaingoatsoftware.com/agile/planning-poker=
" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow"><span style=3D"color: rgb(17,85,=
204);">poker estimation</span></a><span>)</span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: decimal;"><p><span>The product owner and the =
customer start a sprint and pick up a certain number of issues to be addres=
sed. </span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: decimal;"><p><span>The developers takes respo=
nsibility of one or more issues and discuss the estimation</span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: decimal;"><p><span>The product owner check th=
at the estimated story points of all the issues assigned to a developer are=
 consistent with the number of story points (s)he can commit to for the dur=
ation of the sprint. </span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: decimal;"><p><span>A repository for a softwar=
e component that will implement the solution to the issues, or a coherent s=
ubset of them, is created with two branches by default: master and develop.=
 Two build and deployment plans are created on Bamboo, one for each default=
 branch.</span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: decimal;"><p><span>The developer/tester imple=
ments the (automated) acceptance tests for the issues and prepares the data=
 sets for the test (see </span><a href=3D"https://docs.google.com/document/=
d/19fvSInxRvNJXqHwUaHFMj9CR1cUYmd_xwcc1pJJxAJM/edit" class=3D"external-link=
" rel=3D"nofollow"><span style=3D"color: rgb(17,85,204);">Testing Framework=
s</span></a><span>)</span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: decimal;"><p><span>The developer starts a new=
 branch for the issue using the name of the JIRA issue as the name for the =
new branch, solves the issue and execute the unit tests. If the unit tests =
pass, she commits the code to the issue branch writing a comment that start=
s with the issue=E2=80=99s name so that the commit in Bitbucket is linked t=
o the issue in JIRA, set the JIRA issue as resolved and sends a </span><a h=
ref=3D"https://www.atlassian.com/git/tutorials/making-a-pull-request" class=
=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow"><span style=3D"color: rgb(17,85,204);">=
pull request</span></a><span> to the product owner or tester to merge the i=
ssue branch into the development branch, the branch used to merge the branc=
hes created to solve the issues (see </span><a href=3D"https://docs.google.=
com/document/d/1ke-pJE0gD_ZC_g20L5BtS0EuK28EiavHpoJVKWRLSy8/edit#heading=3D=
h.3uo14f5v6wuq" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow"><span style=3D"col=
or: rgb(17,85,204);">Git workflow</span></a><span> for more details) </span=
></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: decimal;"><p><span>The tester and the product=
 owner check visually that the solution passes some quality check, e.g. </s=
pan><a href=3D"https://google.github.io/styleguide/javaguide.html" class=3D=
"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow"><span style=3D"color: rgb(17,85,204);">cod=
ing standard</span></a><span>, best practices such as no copy and paste, us=
e of design patterns, updated documentation. It the solution passes the qua=
lity check it can be merged into the development branch and the artifacts (=
e.g. a Java .jar file created using a develop build plan in Bamboo) will be=
 deployed in the test environment for the integration/acceptance tests. The=
 quality check can also be performed using tools such as </span><a href=3D"=
https://www.sonarqube.org/" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow"><span =
style=3D"color: rgb(17,85,204);">sonarqube</span></a><span>.</span></p></li=
>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: decimal;"><p><span>If the software passes the=
 integration tests (or the acceptance criteria) a release is created with a=
 (</span><a href=3D"https://semver.org/" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nof=
ollow"><span style=3D"color: rgb(17,85,204);">semantic</span></a><span>) ve=
rsion from the development branch and the issue is set to =E2=80=9Cclosed=
=E2=80=9D on JIRA. If one integration test or acceptance test fails, the me=
rged branch that breaks the software must be removed from the development b=
ranch and fixed in its original issue branch (back to step 7)</span></p></l=
i>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: decimal;"><p><span>The new release can be dep=
loyed in production for a certain time (e.g. 1 month) in order to be tested=
 by the users of the system to see whether unforseen bugs are raised. The r=
elease can be set to be used only by a subset of the users of the system.</=
span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: decimal;"><p><span>After the user test time h=
as expired without problems the development branch can be merged into the m=
aster branch and a final release can be created with its own version (using=
 a different build plan) and made available to all the users.</span></p></l=
i>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: decimal;"><p><span>All the issues in the spri=
nt backlog that have not been solved are put back in the product backlog. T=
he velocity of the team (story points done in an iteration) is defined as: =
velocity =3D issues (user story) x story points</span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: decimal;"><p><span>The product owner, the cus=
tomer and the developers/testers meet for the sprint review where the new f=
unctionalities or bug fixes are demonstrated. </span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: decimal;"><p><span>The product owner closes t=
he sprint</span></p></li>
</ol>
<p><span><span><br></span></span></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">A workflow, or workflow scheme, can b=
e shared and reused in different projects. At the IAIS the following workfl=
ow is used</span></p>
